<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900501-0062</DOCNO><DOCID>900501-0062.</DOCID><HL>   U.S. Trade Official Cites   `Helpful' Japanese Actions</HL><DATE>05/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   JAPAN</CO><IN>HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)</IN><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills saidJapan still has barriers to U.S. construction companies, butshe declined to designate it as a country that denies &quot;fairand equal market opportunity&quot; to U.S. companies seekingpublic-works contracts.   Mrs. Hills was required to decide by yesterday whether toinvoke provisions of U.S. law that might be used later to barJapanese companies from bidding for contracts to help buildor supply equipment for U.S. airports.</LP><TEXT>   She noted that Japan has taken some &quot;helpful&quot; steps toopen up its market, and that some new contracts forpublic-works projects in that country have been awarded toU.S. construction companies. She added that the U.S. earlynext month will initiate a new round of talks with Japan on&quot;the whole range of problems related to access to theJapanese market for construction services.&quot;   The U.S., she concluded, will continue to &quot;monitor&quot;Japan's market-opening measures. If the next round ofbilateral negotiations prove to be &quot;unsatisfactory,&quot; shesaid, the Bush administration would consider &quot;appropriateaction.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>